<HEADLINE>
<P>
MINIMALISM DEBATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I agree with the atonalists' argument that minimalism, at its worst, is a far 
too simple reaction to the complexity and austerity of atonality. However, I 
strongly disagree with their assertion that as atonal/serial composers they are 
the sole representatives of High-Art. 
</P>
<P>
They seem to forget the words of the ultimate atonal master, Schoenberg, who 
realized that atonality/serial techniques were not for everyone and that 
(great) music would still be composed in C major. 
</P>
<P>
MATTHEW HETZ 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
