<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON AGING: PARENT CARE NOW TAKES THE MOST YEARS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By The UCLA/USC Longterm Care Gerontology Center 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the first time, American couples are spending more years helping aging 
parents than caring for children, according to a recent report by the Older 
Women's League. It calls the consequences "monumental." 
</P>
<P>
Take the case of Steve and Sara S., both in their 40s. He's a professor; she's 
active in community affairs. Together with their 13-year-old daughter, they 
live in a comfortable home in a small college town in Upstate New York. For 
years they talked about building a house in the country after their daughter 
entered college. Two years ago the plans changed. Steve's bfather was 
hospitalized twice over a period of months, and Steve realized that his father 
could not return home alone. 
</P>
<P>
Steve and his wife invited his father to move in with them for six months. He's 
still there. Says Steve: "My dad has made a life here he never had in New York 
City. He's connected with people. He's a computer whiz in the college course 
he's taking, secretary for the Little League and involved in local 
environmental issues." 
</P>
<P>
The once-temporary move is now permanent, and none of the family members talks 
about change. Steve's dad helps with household chores, supervises his 
granddaughter and insists on paying a small amount for room and board. 
</P>
<P>
There have, of course, been changes. Instead of buying land in the country, 
Sara and Steve enlarged their house to give themselves more privacy. They did 
this just in time; in April, Sara's widowed mother moved in with them as well. 
</P>
<P>
A year before, she suffered a stroke and, although she made a remarkable 
recovery, life isn't the same. She gave up driving, which for her was a link to 
siblings and friends. She visited Steve and Sara monthly, each time staying a 
bit longer. 
</P>
<P>
Experience has taught this intergenerational family what to expect. Sara's 
mother is getting counseling to help her with the transition. Says Steve: 
"She's having a harder time adjusting. She was very much a force in her own 
community and an active church member for 43 years." 
</P>
<P>
Steve and Sara have no complaints about the choices they made. They are 
learning to live with the burdens and joys of aging parents. According to OWL, 
women today can expect to spend 17 years caring for children and 18 years 
assisting a parent. Nearly 2 million women are caring for children and parents 
simultaneously. 
</P>
<P>
Question: I'm a 78-year-old living in Santa Barbara, Calif. Since I retired 20 
years ago, my home has greatly appreciated in value, while my income has 
remained fixed. There are many things I'd like to do and buy, but I am 
concerned about spending my small savings. I've heard about reverse mortgages, 
but very little about sale lease-back plans. Can you tell me about them? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: An increasing number of older people have substantial assets invested 
in their home, but, like you, relatively little income to meet expenses. 
</P>
<P>
According to Dr. Jon Pynoos of USC, aging in place is a strongly held 
preference of most older persons. A recent survey found that 70% of persons age 
65 and above, especially women over 80, agreed with the statement, "What I'd 
really like to do is stay in my own home and never move." Such strong 
attachment to place is associated with the benefits of familiarity, access to 
neighborhood services, proximity of friends, psychological attachments to the 
home and, especially for homeowners, financial security. 
</P>
<P>
Because most older homeowners do not want to move or sell their homes, several 
plans for converting home equity into cash without requiring occupants to 
vacate the residence are available: 
</P>
<P>
Sale lease-back plans were first introduced in 1978 by Fouratt Corp. in an 
attempt to help an elderly Carmel, Calif., resident. According to Rick Watson 
of Fouratt, the woman owned her home free and clear, did not want to move, but 
was living in desperate conditions because of inadequate income. 
</P>
<P>
Under sale lease-back plans, owners sell but retain the right to reside in 
their homes. By contrast, reverse mortgages enable owners to borrow against 
their home equity and repay the loan, usually within 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
In most sale lease-back plans, the owner sells the home to an individual buyer 
or investment firm, then leases it back for lifetime occupancy. If you entered 
into this arrangement, you would become a renter in your home. 
</P>
<P>
The purchase price usually is divided into a lump sum and fixed monthly 
payments in amounts based on the seller's life expectancy. According to Walton, 
the buyer also purchases a deferred annuity for the seller that begins paying 
out when the loan ends. This guarantees the seller regular income over his or 
her lifetime. If the seller dies before the full loan is repaid, the balance is 
paid to the estate. 
</P>
<P>
Seek legal advice to understand the options and risks of both sale lease-back 
and reverse-mortgage plans. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Send questions about growing older to On Aging, P.O. Box 84256, Los Angeles, 
Calif. 90073. Questions of general interest will be answered in the column; 
individual answers cannot be provided. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
