<P>
Photo, Scare tactics -- Charlie Alexander, 14, was one of about 30 costumed 
teen-agers who went trick or treating Saturday night in Woodland Hills. But 
they weren't looking for candy. Instead, they collected food and clothing for 
the homeless who stay at the Valley Shelter in North Hollywood. Dana 
Sonderling, a 14-year-old, and two of her friends conceived the idea weeks ago 
when they talked about how much fun it would be to have a Halloween party. The 
teen-agers passed out bulletins to 100 households notifying them of the 
unorthodox collection. "It's a wacky idea, a Halloween party on Fourth of July 
weekend," said Dana's father, Don Sonderling, but he said the cause made it 
worthwhile. DAVID BOHRER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
